oc:kn_25c9119c a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When translating Python in-place collection mutations to Scala" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Scala collections are immutable by default — operations like :+ (append), ++ (concat), + (map add) create new collections rather than modifying in place. Use map + ('key' -> value) instead of mutation." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Immutability is a core Scala design principle. Understanding that Scala collection operations return new instances is essential for correct translation." .

oc:kn_2d63813c a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing Scala collection transformations" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Prefer Scala's underscore placeholder syntax (_) for simple lambda expressions: nums.map(_ * 2) over nums.map(x => x * 2). Use full lambda syntax only for multi-parameter or complex expressions." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Underscore syntax is more concise and idiomatic Scala, reducing verbosity when translating Python lambda expressions." .

oc:kn_4f0601e9 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When translating Python dictionary access patterns to Scala Map" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Scala's map('key') throws an exception if the key is missing, unlike Python's dct['key'] which raises KeyError. Prefer map.get('key') which returns Option[V], or map.getOrElse('key', default) for safe access." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Scala's Option type provides safer null-handling than exceptions. Using get/getOrElse is idiomatic and avoids runtime crashes." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_51982489 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When translating Python Enum classes to Scala sealed traits/objects" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never use PascalCase for enum case object names in Scala. Always use UPPERCASE (e.g., case object STRING, not case object String)." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Scala convention for constants and enum-like case objects is UPPERCASE, matching Python Enum naming conventions." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_59e89266 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:PreFlightCheck ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Before beginning any Python-to-Scala collection translation" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Before translating Python collection code, identify whether the code uses mutable operations (append, extend, in-place sort). If so, decide whether to use Scala immutable patterns (preferred) or mutable collections." ;
    oc:hasRationale "The mutable vs immutable choice is the single most important architectural decision when translating Python collections to Scala." .

oc:kn_770ed8b4 a oc:Idempotency,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When using Scala immutable collections (default)" ;
    oc:directiveContent "All Scala immutable collection operations are idempotent — calling the same transformation multiple times on the same input produces the same result without side effects." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Immutability guarantees referential transparency and safe reuse of collection values." .

oc:kn_c85c641d a oc:AssumptionBoundary,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When selecting Scala collection types for performance-critical code" ;
    oc:directiveContent "This guide assumes default Scala collections (scala.collection.immutable). It does not cover performance-tuned collections like Vector, Array, or specialized mutable collections unless explicitly noted." ;
    oc:hasRationale "For simple translation tasks, default List/Map/Set suffices, but production code may require choosing the right collection for performance characteristics." ;
    oc:severityLevel "LOW" .

oc:kn_e71fef0b a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When translating Python mutable collection operations to Scala" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never use mutable Scala collections by default; Scala collections are immutable by default. Only use mutable collections (e.g., mutable.ListBuffer) when performance requirements demand it." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Python collections are mutable by default, but Scala's immutable collections are safer, thread-safe, and idiomatic. Translating Python mutation patterns directly to mutable Scala is an anti-pattern." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

